AB  - This chapter was supported in part by the UCLA Depression Grand Challenge. It details the development of an evidence repository for interventions designed to improve mental health knowledge and attitudes in school settings. The repository aims to serve as a comprehensive, accessible resource for schools and organizations, focusing on evaluating mental health interventions' effectiveness and implementation readiness. The chapter outlines the development process, criteria for study evaluation, and its potential to help school communities select effective programs. It also examines the effectiveness of school-based interventions in reducing stigma and improving mental health literacy. Although these interventions show promise in short-term outcomes, their long-term effectiveness remains unclear, with many studies revealing diminished effects over time. The chapter identifies key areas for research, including understanding the ingredients of successful interventions, incorporating behavioral measures rather than just self-reported intentions, and enhancing statistical power in study designs. It emphasizes the need for robust implementation support, such as detailed manuals and organizational purveyors, to ensure the sustainability and fidelity of interventions in school settings. This repository seeks to be a valuable and practical tool for schools and organizations while highlighting areas for future research to foster supportive school environments and contribute to enhancing student mental health. © 2025 John Wiley & Sons, Inc. Published 2025 by John Wiley & Sons, Inc.
