AB  - Research following Hurricane Katrina highlights significant psychological impacts on youth, particularly posttraumatic stress, anxiety, and depression. While most children and adolescents demonstrate adaptability over time, the specific pathways to resilience remain less understood. This study explored longitudinal community data on disaster exposure and traumatic stress across the 10-year recovery period after Katrina. The dataset included 60,703 screenings of children and adolescents from 2005 and 2015 (N = 35,000). Children who met cutoff scores for clinically significant symptoms were compared over time. A series of logistic regressions were conducted to assess factors associated with cutoff scores each year. Results revealed a steady decline in posttraumatic stress: 45% of youth screened positive in 2005 compared to 23% in 2015. The most consistent contributors to elevated symptoms included loneliness, depression, anger, requests to speak with a counselor, and exposure to additional traumas. Other factors—such as property loss, relocation, housing displaced individuals, female gender, older age, and minority status—also contributed, though less strongly and consistently. Findings suggest that immediately after major disasters, roughly half of children experience elevated posttraumatic stress. By the 5-year mark, rates begin to approximate general population concerns (about 25%), with approximately 10% continuing to experience severe or persistent symptoms requiring clinical intervention. These findings underscore the importance of providing school-based mental health education on typical stress reactions and coping strategies, while targeting intensive clinical services for the smaller group with long-term needs. Importantly, youth in this study demonstrated remarkable resilience, offering valuable lessons to guide responses in future disasters. © 2025 American Psychological Association
