AB  - Suicide is an urgent global public health issue. In Muslim countries, suicide stigma and a limited understanding of treatment options persists. Despite the strong evidence for treatment efficacy, public confidence in treatment remains low and individuals with suicidality are not expected to recover fully. Research examining beliefs on the treatability of suicidal behavior within Muslim majority or Muslim minority countries is scarce. This study examines attitudes and beliefs toward the treatability of suicide among the general population in Tajikistan. Using an experimental vignette research design (n = 351), this study explores Tajik people’s beliefs regarding the potential of treating individuals contemplating suicide, the capability of mental health professionals to treat those in such distress, and the likelihood for individuals to recover and resume a normal, productive life. Results demonstrate a significant relationship between mental health knowledge and attitudes toward seeking professional psychological help and treatability, and that there is an interaction effect between age and gender of vignette subject on treatability, with older adults being seen as less treatable than adults or adolescents. This is the first study to explore treatment beliefs about suicidality in Tajikistan and has important implications for mental health literacy and targeted interventions in the region. © 2025 Taylor & Francis Group, LLC.
